\chapter{Related Research}

This chapter presents some relevant literature related to the topic of active object search and also to the subproblems encountered in this thesis. The first section covers some existing approaches to visual active object search. The second section focuses on the detection of objects, while the third section discusses semantic maps and their creation. The last section covers relevant literature to exploration and search planning. 

\section{Active Object Search}

In an active object search task the goal is to find an object as fast as possible by active movement of the used sensors. Without further knowledge this results in a coverage search problem, as for example in this work by Dornhege et al. \cite{coverage}. Additional knowledge about the environment and the searched object can make the search much faster because it allows to reason where the object is more likely. On type of this knowledge is the knowledge about object-object relations, which is for example used by Kollar and Roy \cite{objobj}. A remote is more likely near a sofa than near a sink. Kunze et al.\cite{objobj2} go beyond that and used stricter relation between objects, like a keyboard is usually in front of a monitor. Also useful is knowledge about types of places and the correlation between place type and the object in this place, which is for example used by Viswanathan et al. \cite{objroom}. So is a knife more likely in a kitchen than in a bedroom. 

\section{Object Detection}

The detection of an object is an essential part of an active object search system. In this thesis the task is to find an object of a specified type instead of an object instance. Therefore a general object detector is needed. Visual object detection using convolutional neural networks (CNNs) \cite{CNN} is the most promising method for general object detection at the moment. There the detections are typically in the form of bounding boxes and large datasets exists for training of the CNNs, like PASCAL VOC\cite{voc} and COCO\cite{coco}. One type of architecture used for visual object detection are region-based convolutional neural networks (R-CNNs)\cite{rcnn}. R-CNNs generate in a first step region proposals, which are than classified. However, R-CNNs are slow and even their faster versions Fast R-CNN\cite{fast_rcnn} and Faster R-CNN\cite{faster_rcnn} are computational expensive. There are also visual object detectors using only a single CNN like SSD\cite{ssd} and YOLO\cite{yolo}\cite{yolo2}\cite{yolo3}. YOLO divides the image into a coarse grid. For every grid cells the object probabilities of the detectable object types are predicted. Furthermore, for every cell multiple bounding boxes are predicted, where each bounding box also has a confidence score. The newest version of YOLO, YOLOv3, predicts also at three different scales. All that is done in a single forward pass of the CNN. 

If a point cloud was created together with the image, which is the case if an RGBD-camera was used, the location of the object in 3D space can be estimated. The point cloud can also be used to segment the bounding boxes into object and background. Schwarz et al. \cite{TitanX} used this approach for exact detection of objects for grasping and S{\"{u}}nderhauf et al. \cite{CNN_SLAM} used this to insert objects into semantic maps. 

